I have visited hundreds of marine areas, but there are several that have particularly left a deep impression on me.
The first time I experienced such excitement was ten years ago, off the rugged, undeveloped coast of South Africa.
Every year in June and July, a massive school of sardines migrates northward in an event known as the Sardine Run.
There is a valid reason for this.
It is because hungry and swift predators are secretly chasing after them at an incredible speed.
Generally, dolphins hunt in groups, separating some sardines from the school to create a bait ball, a spherical group.
Chasing the fish to the surface of the sea, they feast on this living and moving delicacy.
There is a shark right behind.
Many people believe that dolphins and sharks are natural enemies, but during the Sardine Run, they actually coexist.
Dolphins help sharks efficiently catch their prey.
Without dolphins, the bait ball would be more dispersed, and sharks would get stuck in what is known as a "sardine donut," filling their mouths with water and gaining nothing.
Now, I have also experienced thrilling moments with sharks during the Sardine Run, and I understand that they do not see me as prey.
However, during this rough feast, they also bump into other fish and get hit by fins like the rest.
When moving east from the coast of Africa and crossing the vast Indian Ocean, you will reach the Maldives, which are made of coral.
During the intense southwest monsoon season, from all over the archipelago, the giant manta rays come to a very small spot in the Ba Atoll called Hanifaru. Usually smaller than a person's eye, a large amount of crustaceans are the main food source for the giant manta rays.
When there is a patch of plankton, the giant manta ray feeds alone and repeatedly somersaults backwards, resembling a puppy chasing its own tail.
However, when plankton gathers in one place, the rays line up in a row and create a long chain for feeding. Even if the rays near the front miss some plankton, the following rays will surely swallow it.
As the amount of plankton increases, the rays swim closer to each other, a unique behavior known as Cyclone Feeding.
The rays, in a solid formation, spiral and form multiple layers of columns, creating a vortex to gather and suck in plankton, then carrying it into their cave-like mouths.
Diving surrounded by a group of hundreds of rays is truly an unforgettable experience.
When I first photographed Hanifaru, it was not under protection and was threatened by development.
By working with NGOs like Manta Trust, my photos eventually helped Hanifaru become a marine protected area.
The fishermen from neighboring islands used to catch rays to make traditional drums out of their skins.
Currently, they are the most dedicated in conservation efforts, and thanks to the rays, the Maldives now earn an additional $8 million in revenue annually.
