This year, I have already worked for National Geographic in the Baja California Peninsula.
About halfway along the Pacific side of the peninsula, there is the San Ignacio Lagoon, which is an important breeding ground for gray whales.
This coastline was a place where mass killings continued for 100 years, with over 20,000 gray whales being killed and only a few hundred surviving.
Currently, the descendants of those whales gently push their own children to the surface of the sea to play and even interact with us.
This species has truly achieved a remarkable revival.
Now, on the opposite side of the peninsula, there is a quiet fishing town called Cabo Pulmo.
It was on the brink of collapse due to decades of overfishing.
In 1995, local fishermen appealed to designate the sea as a marine protected area.
What happened next can only be described as a miracle.
By 2005, only 10 years after the protection began, the number of fish had achieved an unprecedented recovery.
